Data Exploration and Cleaning

My objectives in exploring and cleaning the dataset were to better understand the kinds of patterns and features that might be most relevant to building a quality of contact model and to ensure that there are no obvious problems with the data quality. By exploring the data with various analyses and visualizations, I was able to achieve both goals simultaneously.

Having previously worked with similar datasets, I started my data exploration by looking for ‘No Nulls.’ ‘No Nulls’ batted balls occur when the Trackman system is unable to capture the ball after contact (usually because it was either a sky-high pop-up or a grounder beat into the ground). The stringer at the stadium then records where the ball was fielded and then the missing exit velocity, launch angle, and other variables are then put in retroactively. This means that I can’t be sure that the data is accurate, so I remove all ‘No Nulls’ entries from the dataset to eliminate potential biases later when I train my model.

ggplot(all_bip, aes(x = angle)) +

Most notably, there is a local peak around -20 to -10 degrees that wouldn’t normally be present. Typically, we should expect a fairly normal distribution of batted balls’ launch angle with a dataset of this size.

With a difference so small, and the four other variables all equal, it is reasonable to keep these 18 combinations within the original 368 of non-unique combinations.

I decided to simplify this exploration by just looking at the non-unique combinations of exit speed and launch angle.

exit_angle_group <- all_bip %>%
  group_by(exit_speed, angle) %>%
  summarise(num = n()) %>%
  filter(num > 1) %>%
  arrange(desc(num)) 
exit_angle_group

Here, we see that there are 2,721 non-unique combinations of exit speed and launch angle. Those 2,721 combinations represent 8,022 batted balls making up about 6.5% of the entire dataset. That represented too much of the dataset for me to be comfortable with removing all of those instances.

I decided to increase the minimum number of instances of non-unique exit speed and launch angle combinations to be greater than or equal to five instances. Removing only combinations that had more than five or more observations was a bit arbitrary. Originally, I wanted to remove all non-unique combination observations, but that represented too much of the dataset. I wanted to remove those instances because in this dataset there are over 7,500 unique exit speed values and over 13,500 unique launch angle values. The probability of having two batted balls with the same exit speed and launch angle is just incredibly low. However, I had to balance keeping enough observations for modeling and wanting to protect the dataset from potential biases.

exit_angle_group_5 <- exit_angle_group %>% 
  filter(num > 4)
exit_angle_group_5

With this new criteria, there are 309 non-unique combinations of exit speed and launch angle occurring more than five times. Those 309 combinations represent 1881 batted balls that make up 1.53% of the original dataset. I felt comfortable with removing those 1881 batted balls from the original dataset. We need to remove these batted balls because if we don’t any analysis done will have an inherent bias which will lead to perhaps the wrong conclusions. In the future, if I had more information about each batted ball I’d like to investigate this topic more.

Removing observations from a dataset is not something to do lightly. However, I felt it was necessary to remove the observations with five or more instances of the same exit speed and launch angle. As I said above, the probability of this occurring is so highly unlikely, that these batted balls must have been ‘no nulls’ and their exit speed and launch angles retroactively imputed. When looking at the launch angles of these combinations with five or more observations, there is a gap visible. The launch angle has a range of -45.35 to -10.82 and then the next launch angle is at 54.82 going to 70.18 (with seven instances of 121.42 launch angle, which is a major outlier). We know (https://tht.fangraphs.com/43416-2/) that Trackman has issues handling grounders and pop-ups and this further reinforces that claim. With removing these non-unique observations, we can be sure that the dataset only contains only measured batted balls.

Methodology and Design Decisions

To create a quality of contact metric, I created a multi-class classification model that aims to predict the play result using a XGBoost model. XGBoost is a decision tree based ensemble supervised machine learning algorithm that uses a gradient boosting framework. Gradient boosting is a case of boosting where errors are minimized by gradient descent and applies the principle of boosting weak learners. The rationale for using XGBoost lies in its easy to understand nature and the structure and size of the data. Decision trees for classifications are easy to interpret on a fundamental level. A basic decision tree, for example just a tree stump, visualized it is easy to see the rationale for the classification. Since this dataset is relatively large (over 100,000 observations) and is tabular data, gradient boosting machines (GBMs), specifically XGBoost seems like a fine choice for this problem. Also, GBMs are non-parametric models that are suitable for this non-linear data.

For my modeling, I decided on using the play result as the response variable. The play result (out, single, double, triple, homerun, sacrifice, fielder’s choice, and error) is a good starting place for measuring quality of contact. If we are just looking at grading quality of contact based on the result of the batted ball then we know that a homerun is better than a triple which is better than a double and so on. This metric provides a broadly accepted way to rank the quality of a batted ball. Generally speaking, hitting a ball harder (more exit speed) is better than hitting a ball softer. However, it’s important to include the launch angle when using exit speed. A batter would much rather hit a ball 105 mph at 25 degrees than a ball 125 mph at -10 degrees. There are exceptions, but in the aggregate we know that homeruns have the best combination of exit speed and launch angle. However, there is more to assessing quality of contact than just exit speed and launch angle, such as launch direction, bearing, and distance. Each of the metrics individually can provide some insight about the quality of contact, but when taken together it quickly becomes intractable to rank every possible combination. From this, I felt that all of these metrics were best captured and ranked by the play result.

Feature Selection

In the given dataset there were fifteen columns not including the selected response variable, play_result. I ran a Boruta feature selection method on fourteen features (all but RowNum and play_result) to see which features are important on the outcome, play_result. Running the Boruta algorithm on the entire dataset returned that all attributes were confirmed to be important.

Even though the Boruta indicated that all features were important, I decided to not include pa_of_inning, pitch_of_ab, outs, and hit_type in my modeling. The decision to not include the plate appearance of the inning was because I didn’t think that a batter should gain or lose credit for quality of contact based on when the plate appearance occurred in an inning. Additionally, outs were not included for the same reason. The pitch number of the at-bat was not included because the count was already present in the modeling and including both felt redundant as the count is an accurate representation of how many pitches were in the at-bat. In the case of multiple foul balls, where the number of pitches is greater than the sum of balls and strikes, the hitter will have the same number of strikes. A homerun hit on a 3-0 count is very different than a 0-2 count. Assuming the quality of contact is the same, a batter should get more credit for the ball hit on 0-2 than 3-0. A batter shouldn’t get more credit for a batted ball that was hit on the fifth pitch of an at bat versus the tenth pitch. Similarly, hit type was not included because the information gained from that feature is already present in the angle variable.

Feature Engineering

There were a few augmentations I made to make the dataset ready to be used in XGBoost modeling. The first was to change the nature of the response variable, the play result. Originally, there were nine unique play results: Out, Single, Double, Triple, HomeRun, FieldersChoice, Sacrifice, Error, and Undefined. I grouped FieldersChoice, Sacrifice, and Error into the Out category as they are all essentially the same thing. I then removed all pitches with the play result Undefined. Trying to classify a batted ball into the Undefined category doesn’t glean any insights into the quality of contact and since that category only has 76 observations and represents 0.06% of the dataset I felt comfortable with removing that class of play results. Lastly, because XGBoost only deals with numeric columns I encoded each play result type as an integer, one through five, each representing an out, single, double, triple, or homerun.

For the purposes of simplifying the XGBoost modeling, I considered change-ups and splitters to be the same. They were both grouped together as change-ups. I also grouped ‘Undefined’ and knuckleball pitch-types into the same category as ‘Other.’

Earlier, I also created one feature for the count, combining the strike and ball features into one variable.

There are four categorical variables that were included in the model: batter_side, pitcher_throws, tagged_pitch_type, and count. As mentioned above, since XGBoost can only handle numeric variables, I changed each of those variables into a numeric one by creating dummy variables. For example, for both batter_side and pitcher_throws there will be one new column batter_side_right and pitcher_throws_right, respectively. Those two columns would equal “1” if the pitcher or batter throws right, and 0 otherwise. There were seven dummy columns created for tagged_pitch_type (cutter, curveball, sinker, slider, fastball, change-up, and other), and twelve columns for count.

Analysis/Model Selection

Once the data was prepared for XGBoost modeling, I divided the cleaned dataset into two datasets: train and test. I used a stratified 70/30 split to ensure that the train and test datasets would be split evenly by the response variable, play result.

Baseline Model

I started the modeling by doing a simple 10-fold cross-validation to determine the appropriate number of iterations to use in a baseline XGBoost model. There were two main choices I made in the XGBoost modeling. I decided to use multi:softprob as the objective of the model with mlogloss evaluation metric. multi:softprob returns the probability of each observation being a member of each class. There are five classes of the response variable (Out, Single, Double, Triple, and Homerun). I made this choice because you can gain more information about each batted ball knowing the probability of it belonging to each class rather than the model returning which class has the maximum probability. The evaluation metric is used for validation data in both the cross-validation and XGBoost modeling for both early stopping and model evaluation. mlogloss is the loss function used in multinomial logistic regression and is defined as the negative log-likelihood of a logistic model that returns probabilities for its training data. The baseline model also has no hyperparameters specified, meaning that all of those parameters are their default values. I decided to run a baseline model in order to compare it with a hyperparameter tuned model. A baseline model is a good place to start as it is fast and easy to run, and we can’t tell if a future model is any good in a vacuum. Meaning that even if a model returns a 95% accuracy we don’t know if the model is any good because there theoretically could be a model with different hyperparameters that returns a 99% accuracy.

XGBoost Baseline Modeling 

baseline_cv <- xgboost::xgb.cv(params = list(objective = "multi:softprob", eval_metric = c("mlogloss"), num_class = 5), data = x_train, nrounds = 2500, early_stopping_rounds = 10, nfold=10, stratified = T)

base_mod <- xgboost::xgboost(params = list(objective = "multi:softprob", eval_metric = c("mlogloss"), num_class = 5), data = x_train, nrounds = baseline_cv$best_ntreelimit)

Hyperparameter Tuning

I used a Latin hypercube for hyperparameter tuning. The Latin hypercube is a space-filling design that aims at filling the hyperparameter space as well as possible, so it’s not necessary to run a model for every unique hyperparameter combination. The Latin hypercube creates 30 rows of different combinations of six hyperparameters (eta, gamma, subsample, colsample_bytree, max_depth, and min_child_weight). Then each combination was run through a 10-fold cross-validation using early stopping rounds to see which combination performed the best on the train set. The best performing combination was then used in one final XGBoost model to compare with the baseline model.

XGBoost Hyperparameter Tuning

grid <- dials::grid_latin_hypercube(
  dials::finalize(dials::mtry(), train_data),
  dials::min_n(),
  dials::tree_depth(),
  dials::learn_rate(),
  dials::loss_reduction(),
  sample_size = dials::sample_prop(),
  size = 30
)

grid <- grid %>%
  mutate(
    learn_rate = .225 + .1 * ((1 : nrow(grid)) / nrow(grid)),
    # has to be between 0 and 1
    mtry = scales::rescale(mtry, to=c(0,1))
  )

get_metrics <- function(df, row = 1) {
  
  params <-
    list(
      booster = "gbtree",
      objective = "multi:softprob", 
      eval_metric = c("mlogloss"), 
      num_class = 5,
      eta = df$learn_rate,
      gamma = df$loss_reduction,
      subsample= df$sample_size,
      colsample_bytree= df$mtry,
      max_depth = df$tree_depth,
      min_child_weight = df$min_n
    )
  
  # tuning with cv
  fd_model <- xgboost::xgb.cv(data = x_train, params = params, nrounds = 2500, nfold = 10, stratified = T, 
                              metrics = list("mlogloss"), early_stopping_rounds = 10, print_every_n = 10)
  
  output <- params
  output$iter = fd_model$best_iteration
  output$logloss = fd_model$evaluation_log[output$iter]$test_mlogloss_mean
  output$error = fd_model$evaluation_log[output$iter]$test_merror_mean
  
  this_param <- bind_rows(output)
  
  return(this_param)
}

results_train <- map_df(1 : nrow(grid), function(x) {

Model Feature Importance

importance <- xgboost::xgb.importance(feature_names = colnames(final_model), model = final_model)
xgboost::xgb.ggplot.importance(importance_matrix = importance)

Here we can see the feature importance of the final XGBoost model. Generally, feature importance provides a score that indicates how useful or valuable each feature was in the construction of the boosted decision trees within the model. The more an attribute is used to make key decisions with the decision trees, the higher its relative importance. From the results above, it is clear that distance was the most important feature in modeling the outcome of the play result. Inherently, that makes a lot of sense. It’s really hard to hit a homerun that goes five feet or hit a single that goes 450 feet. Following distance are the four other batted ball characteristics: angle, direction, exit speed, and bearing. Initially, I thought those five features would be the most influential in a model that aims to predict the play result and that was true.

From the chart above, we can see that the model had the hardest time correctly predicting triples, only getting 1/759 correct. QC+ Metric Creation

After using the best performing model to obtain predictions for each observation, I created my metric, Quality of Contact Plus (QC+). To generate QC+ values, I take the weighted on-base average (wOBA) linear weights for a single, double, triple, and homerun averaged over the last six seasons (2015-2020) and multiply those values by the probability of each batted ball belonging to each class. For example, say the model returned the probability of a batted ball belonging to the out class as 0.75, a single 0.20, and a double .05. I then multiplied those values by the corresponding wOBA values. For my example that would be (0 * .75) + (.878167 * .20) + (1.23867 * .05) = 0.2375669. Here the wOBA value for a single is .878167 and double 1.23867. This process returns a weighted likelihood value. I then took all of the weighted likelihoods and scaled them to a mean of 100 with a standard deviation of 30. I picked 100 as the mean to make my QC+ metric similar to publicly available metrics such as wRC+, OPS+, DRC+, and others. I selected a standard deviation of 30 because the standard deviation for wRC+ in 2019 was 29.64 and it made sense to calibrate it to a similar scale.

woba_weights_2015_2020_avg <- c(0, .878167, 1.23867, 1.5633, 2.00167) # from FanGraphs

full_preds_v2 %<>%
  mutate(prob_times_woba_weight = (out.prob * woba_weights_2015_2020_avg[1]) + (single.prob * woba_weights_2015_2020_avg[2]) + 
           (double.prob * woba_weights_2015_2020_avg[3]) + (triple.prob * woba_weights_2015_2020_avg[4]) + 
           (hr.prob * woba_weights_2015_2020_avg[5]))

full_preds_v2$percentile <- 100 * (scales::rescale(full_preds_v2$prob_times_woba_weight, to=c(0,1)))
full_preds_v2$qcp <- psych::rescale(full_preds_v2$percentile, mean = 100, sd = 30, df=F)
full_preds_v2$qcp_rd <- round(full_preds_v2$qcp)

full_preds_v2 <- full_preds_v2[, c(1:12, 35:45, 13:34)]

full_preds_v2_cleaned <- full_preds_v2[, c(1:23)]

Below is a simple table showing the average QC+ for each hit type. This follows our intuition that line drives have the best outcomes and popups have the worst. It’s interesting to see, however, that bunts and ground balls have very similar average QC+.

full_preds_v2_cleaned %>%

In this diagram we can see the corresponding ‘hot’ spots for the QC+ metric. It’s important to note that here the x axis is the bearing of the batted ball and not the x-coordinate location. This is a great way to see QC+ validated. The fielder positions are placed based on the average location of each defender from the last five seasons, taken from baseballsavant.com. These positions correspond to the ‘cool’ zones of QC+. Focusing on the infield, we can see the hot zones in the gaps between the average location of the infielders. For example, to the left of third base and to the right of first base those would be singles, doubles, or triples, down the line getting past the respective defenders at their base. We can also see the gap between the infielders and outfielders where we would expect bloop singles or doubles falling in between the defenders. Also, the power alleys are visible between the corner outfielders and the centerfielder. Most notably, batted balls that are typical homerun distance are the brightest spots on the diamond. All of this comes together nicely to validate the success of my QC+ metric.
